de.systemagmbh.interfaces.logger
Interface ISysLogConstants

All Superinterfaces:
ISysDevelopmentLogSwitch, ISysGlobal
All Known Implementing Classes:
ASysBus, ASysLogger, ASysService, CSysCheckerByLevelCombination, CSysCheckerByLevelRange, CSysLog, CSysLogConstantsConverter
public interface ISysLogConstants
extends ISysDevelopmentLogSwitch, ISysGlobal

All important constants for logging are defined here.
These are the supported log levels, a switch to turn off developer log output for delivery (inherited from ISysDevelopmentLogSwitch), the default log type (NO_LOG_TYPE) and some String constants for building unified log output.

The supported log levels are in order of heaviness:

- FATAL
- ERROR
- WARNING
- ALWAYS
- COM
- STEP
- INFO
- METHOD
- ALL

The constant NO_LOG_TYPE is the default value for each logger. (See ASysLogger.) It can be set by the individual application to any other value bigger 0. If method log of CSysLog is called with the parameter logType the given value is checked and only if it corresponds to the set log type of the logger the message is logged.

The constants for building unified log output can to be used in the following way:

public void methodA()
{
final String method = "methodA(): ";
CSysLog.log("Comp", IN+method, ISysLogConstants.METHOD);
//-- Do anything
methodB();
CSysLog.log("Comp", OUT+method, ISysLogConstants.METHOD);
}

public void methodB()
{
final String method = "methodB(): ";
CSysLog.log("Comp", IND+IN+method, ISysLogConstants.METHOD);
if(nothingToDo)
{
CSysLog.log("Comp", IND+NEG+method, ISysLogConstants.METHOD)
return;
}
//-- Do anything
CSysLog.log("Comp", IND+OUT+method, ISysLogConstants.METHOD);
}

As you can see the methodB uses the IND to get an indent related to methodA for all its output. This makes log output much better readable.
